Not really.  It's what pretty much every country that has a half decent or better economy does.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Some areas also make extensive use of toll roads (I HATE toll roads and go out of my way to avoid using them).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Toll roads are a dumb idea.  The biggest problem with the one's here is that if you don't either pay before traveling or pay within the day after traveling they give you a $100 fine for it.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So what is some ditz has a big gas-guzzler. Yes it’s an ostentations display of wealth, but they have the money so let them.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If they want to show their wealth they'd be better off buying a Merc or BMW.  Shows that they have a lot of money much better then an off-road vehicle.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As for their relative inability to drive, well licensing should be stricter – I agree with that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
All licencing should be stricter, and people who can't obey the road rules should be punished more.  Less fines and more licence suspensions should be the policy on road rule breaking.  It might also get around the revenue raising objections those who speed always seem to make.<br>
<br>
It isn't just 4x4 drivers who are terrible although they are a lot of them.  It is likely due to a few factors:<br>
1: 4 wheel drives are harder to drive then passenger cars.<br>
2: Those that drive 4 wheel drives can often think they own the road because they have the biggest car<br>
3: 4 wheel drives are very common becuase of their percieved safety (despite them usually not being as safe as large passenger cars).<br>
<br>
A lot of people driving passenger cars are pretty bad too.  Even those driving small cars can still manage to be terrible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have not seen a LPG conversion, but then again I do live in the US and we barely have public busses that use LPG. Is it comparable to Gasoline engines in power? What is the cost of such a conversion, and how does the fuel cost compare to gasoline? What is the range of the vehicles? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Busses on LPG?  I haven't seen any, their either diesel or natural gas (some of the newest ones) although cars running on LPG are everywhere in Australia.  LPG conversion does cause a loss in power but with the engines that are most often converted (usually &gt; 3.0 L V6 or <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  it probably wouldn't be noticable although with smaller engines it would be.  The conversion usually costs a few thousand dollars to do and the fuel is a bit less then half the cost of ULP here, mainly becuase it isn't taxed as much (if they taxed it as much as petrol it would probably only cost a little bit less).  The range of LPG cars would depend on the tank size although it would probably be about the same as with ULP.  Most LPG cars here a dual fuel so they could get very good range by running on LPG until the tank is empty then switching over to Petrol. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uscoobaru.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scoobaru</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/10/02 11:03:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Sorry, I just do not agree with your conclusions. </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Not really. It's what pretty much every country that has a half decent or better economy does.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Appeal to majority or authority, definitional logical fallacy.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Toll roads are a dumb idea. The biggest problem with the one's here is that if you don't either pay before traveling or pay within the day after traveling they give you a $100 fine for it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Pay as you drive is a much better idea and a rather workable idea.  Anyone who has driven on highways around Chicago and into Indiana will attest to this.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> They can afford to pay it. I don't really need to say anything more about it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Believe in any form of rights?  You can 'afford' or 'deal with' having your freedom of speech restricted on discussing tax systems, so does that mean that my government body is justified in limiting what you say merely because you can 'afford' it?<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Example with a 20% rate the person on $10 000 would only be able to spend $8 000 whereas the person making $100 000 with a 20% rate would earn $80 000.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
First response to this was stated above, simply being able to afford something doesn't make it OK.  Many proponents of a flat tax system make allowances for this:  up to half the poverty level or thereabout, there is no tax on income.  So if in your example the poverty line was $10,000, the example would have the poorer man paying $1000 instead of $2000 (only taxing $5000 @ 20%, the other half at zero percent)<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Or maybe it's called a regressive tax because it is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Call it a flat tax, THAT is what it is.<br>
<br>
You sir, present no valid arguments agaist a flat tax system. <p>Scoobaru
