'97 Subaru Impreza</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 321<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/11/02 2:13:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Sorry, I just do not agree with your conclusions. </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Appeal to majority or authority, definitional logical fallacy.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not always.  Sometimes the reason it is in the majority is because it works better then the alternatives.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pay as you drive is a much better idea and a rather workable idea. Anyone who has driven on highways around Chicago and into Indiana will attest to this.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If it uses toll booths it's a useless congestion causing system probably designed in a conspiracy of the oil companies to sell more petrol by keeping cars idleing more.  Funding by petrol tax is the best way because it means people pay by how much they drive and also get to pay more if they drive a bigger car thus encouraging some people to buy more environmentally friendly cars.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Believe in any form of rights? You can 'afford' or 'deal with' having your freedom of speech restricted on discussing tax systems, so does that mean that my government body is justified in limiting what you say merely because you can 'afford' it?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Maybe you should learn a bit about need.  The government needs to get some money from taxes.  Now to do that they have two choices.  Either they just slug everyone the same amount regardless of whether they can afford it or not or they can make those who can't afford to pay much not pay much but those that can afford it pay more.  Governments aren't automatically justified in taking something because they can afford it but if they have to take something away from people they may as well take it from those who can afford to lose it then those that can't.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> First response to this was stated above, simply being able to afford something doesn't make it OK.  Many proponents of a flat tax system make allowances for this: up to half the poverty level or thereabout, there is no tax on income. So if in your example the poverty line was $10,000, the example would have the poorer man paying $1000 instead of $2000 (only taxing $5000 @ 20%, the other half at zero percent)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Wouldn't that make it a slightly progressive system?<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Call it a flat tax, THAT is what it is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
