<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As for the mass deforestation in third world countries, again we do not support it – but how are we to stop it? Now that we (the industrialized nations) have climbed to the top of the heap, do we tell everyone else they cannot emulate us? Yea, that will work. We come across as hypocrites. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Provide alternatives so that they don't have to remove their forests.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Do we support the free market – Yes. No better system exists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Only to some extent.  Markets are great but they do need to be regulated.  Usually a lot more then most libertarians claim.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I feel many of our arcane laws that create Corporations as entities (leaving the board members and stockholders with little or no liability for corporate misdeeds) are wrong and should be changed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Limited liability should really be removed.  If a company goes bankrupt but the board aren't at fault then I don't really see the point of punishing them but if the board mismanged it then they should be the ones that suffer the consquences of it.  Right now it's the workers and shareholders that suffer when a company is mismanged (usually the workers suffer more).<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It would be a vastly different world if the Ford could be held accountable for the diseases caused by auto pollution (i.e. – the massive increase in asthma).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Or regulations requireing cars to reduce pollution could be passed.  Give them 5 years to comply and if they don't then fine them a billion dollars a year until they comply.  That would also do.  The problem with holding a company liable for pollution is that determine the value of the damages is very hard and often it isn't economic damage but loss of lifespan.  Preventing the pollution in the first place is better then letting people die so taht someone could be sued later.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I think the best argument against Libertarianism is it is somewhat utopian.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's a good argument against it.  But the argument about it not being workable is even better.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Libertarians tend to believe that people will play fair, and we all know they wont.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If people don't play fair then it probably will never work.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But as far a utopian ideals go, Libertarianism is a pretty benign one.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Now it is.  But I would not be suprised if Libertarianism becomes the next communism.  Afterall it is opposite and equal to it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uscoobaru.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scoobaru</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/02 12:25:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay, as a Libertarian I do take some offense…</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You see progressive tax may not be the best system there is. It's just the best one we know of. Sure it may have problems but it works better then all the alternatives we know of.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, in 1383, oppressive monarchy was the 'best alternative we knew of', so does that mean that it is the way to go?  You still haven't dealt with the argument that an appeal to authority is a logical fallacy and proof of nothing.<br>
