<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It's very easy to look at the situtation in such a way that shows the rich to be robbers who steal from their workers by not paying them the full value of their labour.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No.  Simple economics says otherwise.  The system you would thus promote is necessarily a communist one, and a free market it out of the question.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Afterall what does a poor person need with an organisation to overthrow foreign democracies?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
What does a rich person need a public hospital for?  Or public education?  But that isn't really the point.  Desert Storm wasn't only protecting the rich, it was protecting everyone's oil supply.  Letting Iraq's actions go unchecked would have a serious effect on everyone, poor included.  In fact, based on your argument about what they can afford, it protected the poor MORE than the rich.  A 50 cent increase in case would be proportionally more for a poor person than a rich person.  The military should be soley financed out of the little man's pocket, eh?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> LOL. Taking money from those who can't afford it is a bad idea. The follow the money argument basically says take the money from those that can afford to lose it. It's quite a good way to do things.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
