<br>
As for the philosophy of Libertarians being very basic, you are correct. Libertarians tend to be highly individualistic, and organization is not our strong suit – Collectivists are much better at that. So, any unifying principals we have tend to be very basic; even then we vary. Another Libertarian would probably have a completely different definition.<br>
<br>
Any philosophy, doctrine, or idea taken to extreme is dangerous. Libertarianism could be dangerous if it were to suppress all other options and allow now dissention – a highly unlikely thing. <br>
<br>
Regulation is a form of law, and I have no philosophical opposition to reasonable regulation. However, you have to think things through. Lets take your idea about requiring auto manufacturers to reduce pollution. Taking a chance that I might slip on a logical fallacy here, what if they comply but the cars now double in price because of the new required pollution controls. Sales might drop, forcing them to lay off employees. The poor would not be able to afford the new cars, so they would have to continue to use the more polluting, older vehicles – unfairly subjecting them to higher exposure to pollution. I guess you could mandate people into having to replace their older cars, but again this would unfairly affect the poor. We could cap the price the companies could sell them for, but if we do that and they cannot make a reasonable profit then they may very well get out of the business; at the very least people would not be as likely to invest in said company. <br>
<br>
As for the deforestation issue, well duhh! Of course if we should provide alternatives. Gee, problem solved! It was so simple, just provide alternatives! <br>
Like what? Ah, there is the problem. Damnit, and I thought we had this one licked. <br>
<br>
Have you read Ayn Rand? Do you know anything about her, other than she is the evil progenitor of Objectivism and that damn book (which I think should be required reading)? I can see disagreeing with her conclusions. There is even a valid argument that she wasn’t that original, just taking ideas that were already out there (like that is a crime). I can see disliking her personally (which, based on what I know of her, I would. I do not like “Guru’s”). But not intelligent, no – you are wrong. Calling someone stupid because you do not agree with them is a sign of a weak argument on your part.  <br>
<br>
Funny, I have always thought you would make a great <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.aynrand.org/objectivism/essentials.html">Objectivist</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (and, if we go back to her damn book, I have kind of pictured you as Ragnar Danneskjold).  They reject anything that cannot be proven. Personally, I have always found them to be a bit harsh.  <p>Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 340<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/02 6:41:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay, as a Libertarian I do take some offense…</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Well, in 1383, oppressive monarchy was the 'best alternative we knew of'<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
