<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  so does that mean that it is the way to go? You still haven't dealt with the argument that an appeal to authority is a logical fallacy and proof of nothing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Actually.  The present state of economics is that progressive taxes are the best we know of.  If you want to dispute that you better provide proof.  I don't have to prove anything until you've done some proof.<br>
<br>
Those that thought that oppressive monarchy wasn't the best system tried out their own ones.  Some of them ended up failing but democracy worked better then monarchy.  If there were proof that a 'flat' tax rate were the best system then I'd support it.  But until I get shown that proof I won't support it.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Failed completely to address what I said. Just because we can produce a net benefit does not mean it is OK. How about another example? Instead of killing 20,000, we'll just steal the healthy organs of 80,000.  Those 80,000 can 'afford' to give up those organs, right? That is A-OK to take, in that case!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There's a big difference between life and property.  They are treated differently by all good governments.  Life is something that usually can not be taken away unless absolutely neccessary (usually only to prevent you killing someone when there is no other way) whereas property is something that a person has which can be taken away if it's neccessary.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  OK, here you have just defended the two points that I have only claimed are irrelevent.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Just because they are irrelavant to you doesn't mean they're irrelavant.  Most people probably do consider them to be relavant.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  First, the end result of it economically and on people. I don't care.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It does matter to me and it probably matters are great deal to the people the tax system will be imposed on.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  What I do care about is my 'extremist ideology' of equal treatment under the law and individual property rights.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Equal treatment under the law is a good idea and individual property rights are also useful but one must realise that property rights can not be absolute.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Second, the idea that the majority must be right.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The majority are often wrong.  Thing is doing what they want means less chance of a rebellion.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  It doesn't, but in this case you are trying to argue that it does.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Majorites don't produce truth very well but they produce peace.  Basically what that means is that under a democracy there is a lot less chance of a civil war.  If you bring in a system without majority consent then you'll need a dictatorship with a strong military to keep it in place.  Even then you'll have trouble.<br>
<br>
That's why libertarianism won't work in any country that now exists.  The majority won't let you implement it.  Even if they did the results (which is what matters to most people) will cause the system to be disposed of.<br>
<br>
You might be more interested in the principles then the results, but those that live under the system will be more interested in results.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  No. Simple economics says otherwise. The system you would thus promote is necessarily a communist one, and a free market it out of the question.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
