<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  In fact, based on your argument about what they can afford, it protected the poor MORE than the rich.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
An increase in the cost of oil would have reduce profit margains of many companies quite a bit.  Thus affecting the rich more.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The point here is that if the government services shoudl be paid for by those who use them<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Government often fills the role of providing services to those who couldn't otherwise afford them.  With some government services (e.g. welfare) if a person is on it couldn't afford to pay for it if they had to.  Proof that privatising everything won't help with poverty.  The poor can't afford to pay so we have the middle class and rich pay instead.  In theory the poor person will also be helped by the government and possibly the private sector to get a job and get off welfare.  In practice a lot of the people who go on welfare are there as transient welfare recipients who might just lose their job for a bit of time then manage to find another one but who couldn't support themselves for the time between jobs.<br>
<br>
Finding a way to pay for government services means find where the money is.  Notice how most businesses allow use of concession cards to get discounts.  Those over a certain age, those who are unemployed and those who are full time students can often get discounts at the expense of those who aren't paying full price.  That's basically how progressive taxes work although they have more divisions.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The closest we have ever come to a libertarian society is in the early days of America, through most of the 1800s. So did America fall apart during that period? No. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
During the 1800s in the US all the things libertarians hate except income tax were in the US.  although it should be noted that most states had a head tax or property tax that was the equivalent of income tax.<br>
<br>
Sure the federal government back then didn't have anywhere near as much power as today but the states more then made up for the lack of federal tyrany.  You also had slavery back then.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Logical fallacy - Appeal to Popularity – Arguing wide use of something as proof it is good is a logical failure. Yes, if something works then it is very likely to become popular; but that does not make the argument valid.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If the reason it's popular is that it's the best avilable then it is valid.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Another Libertarian would probably have a completely different definition.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's one of the ways in which libertarianism is equal to communism.  There were many different varieties of communism which mostly seemed to hate each other just as much as they hated the capitalist pigs.  There are a lot of arguments between the different variants of libertarianism which echo the communist arguments.  A lot of them accuse other libertarians who only slightly disagree of being statists (which is a complement).<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Any philosophy, doctrine, or idea taken to extreme is dangerous. Libertarianism could be dangerous if it were to suppress all other options and allow now dissention – a highly unlikely thing. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Some ideas just have to be implemented to be dangerous.  With libertarianism it would probably be dangerous even if it allowed people to speak out against it.  Just look at what Russia is like (it's very close to libertarianism at the moment).<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  However, you have to think things through. Lets take your idea about requiring auto manufacturers to reduce pollution. Taking a chance that I might slip on a logical fallacy here, what if they comply but the cars now double in price because of the new required pollution controls.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The market is very good at making things cheaply if needed.  Regulation in the past has this tendency of not costing anywhere near as much to implement then what industry says it will.  In fact most of the time it costs a lot less then even the EPA say it will.<br>
<br>
This is because companies will often try new technologies and methodologies to allow them to implement the change cheaper once it has become clear to them that their lobbists couldn't provide big enough bribes to stop the legislation.  When CFCs were banned it cost Nortel one million dollars to purchase new equipment that didn't require CFCs.  They end saving four million dollars because the new chemicals were a lot cheaper to buy and dispose of.<br>
<br>
If the car company says it'll double the cost.  The EPA will probably say the cost will go up 20%.  In reality it'll probably only go up 3 to 10% and end up saving money in the long term.<br>
<br>
There's some examples of what I'm talking about at <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.prospect.org/print/V8/35/goodstein-e.html">www.prospect.org/print/V8...ein-e.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
