I find it a bit disconcerting that you dismiss “Atlas Shrugged” without having reviewed it yourself. As I stated earlier, I think it should be required reading. As for its reviews, it gets quite a few positive ones – people either love it or they hate it, there is very little middle ground. Honestly, I don’t expect you will like it. We all have our biases, and I expect you will think the book drivel. Still, know thy enemy!<br>
<br>
Self-interest was repudiated? By who, and when? <br>
<br>
Here are the four basic principles of Objectivism, as defined by Rand:<br>
<br>
1. Reality exists as an objective absolute - facts are facts, independent of man's feelings, wishes, hopes or fears.<br>
<br>
2. Reason (the faculty which identifies and integrates the material provided by man's senses) is man's only means of perceiving reality, his only source of knowledge, his only guide to action, and his basic means of survival.<br>
<br>
3. Man - every man - is an end in himself, not the means to the ends of others. He must exist for his own sake, neither sacrificing himself to others nor sacrificing others to himself. The pursuit of his own rational self-interest and of his own happiness is the highest moral purpose of his life.<br>
<br>
4. The ideal political-economic system is laissez-faire capitalism. It is a system where men deal with one another, not as victims and executioners, nor as masters and slaves, but as traders, by free, voluntary exchange to mutual benefit. It is a system where no man may obtain any values from others by resorting to physical force, and no man may initiate the use of physical force against others. The government acts only as a policeman that protects man's rights; it uses physical force only in retaliation and only against those who initiate its use, such as criminals or foreign invaders. In a system of full capitalism, there should be (but, historically, has not yet been) a complete separation of state and economics, in the same way and for the same reasons as the separation of state and church<br>
<br>
As for her not being as intelligent as the Objectivists like to make her out to be – of course. People always try and elevate their leaders. A lot of people who supported Clinton still pretend he is a moral and honest man when, as we know, he is a sleazebag. Just because someone is a nasty individual does not make the wrong. Oh, if only the world were that easy.  <br>
 <br>
I agree about providing nuclear power to the third world, unfortunately our government’s fear the technology would be used to produce weapons. If we elevate everyone’s standard of living, the desire for conflict will diminish and we would all benefit. Fear stand in our way.<br>
<br>
Most deforestation in the third world is not for fuel, but for land. They need grazing and farm land to support their exploding populations. They have access to the benefits of the first world (medicines, etc.) that greatly reduce mortality without actually changing their basic culture – they breed like bunnies. This is a good survival trait if you have a limited lifespan, but it is becoming a problem now. The deforestation is just a symptom of our population explosion.  <p>Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 652<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/02 5:18:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Rand</span><hr size=1> So many benefits to the third world and our own are being blocked by this fear of weapons development. In truth our fear is making the problem worse. Aswell as deforestation we face an escalating greenhouse effect from fossil fuels. Turning our backs on atomic power has given the rest of the world several decades to catch up with us. Other countries don't always share our nuclearphobia and are prepared to begin their own reactor programs. With or without our help. The likelihood of an accident would be lessened if we lent our experience.<br>
